R. Greg Stacey, Nichollas E. Scott, Leonard J. Foster

flowRoot.flowPara: Protein complexes are ubiquitous and central
to the function of cellular life.
One method to identifiy protein complexes
In PCP, complexes are identified as proteins
that "travel together" across a separation gradient.
The bioinformatics pipeline below uses PCP-
SILAC data to 1) detect changes in protein levels between conditons, 2) predict interactions between protein pairs, and 3) predict protein complexes across conditions.

The pipeline detects chromatogram peaks and reports the relative protein amounts between experimental conditions. Changes in protein amounts between conditions ("fold changes") are reported, and statistical significance is assessed using hypothesis testing (t-test, rank-sum test) across replicates.
Protein-protein interactions are predicted by a machine learning classifier.
Each pair of chromatograms is compared to CORUM gold standards.
A Naive Bayes classifier assigns an interaction score to each chromatogram pair.
Finally, a threshold is applied to all scores to determine interacting pairs.
The bioinformatics pipeline above predicts protein interactions and complexes in conditional co-fractionation experiments.
The CORUM database is used as a gold standard reference, although any database of complexes could be used, e.g. STRING.
False positive interactions are minimized by controlling the precision, TP / (TP + FP), of the final interaction list.
